 reform. Drawing on interviews with 163 participants in the provinces of Henan and Jiangsu, as well as government documents and elite memoirs, biographies, speeches, and reports, Manning offers a new theoretical lens—attachment politics—to underscore how family and ideology intertwined to create an important building block of state capacity and governance.As The Party Family details, infant mortality in China dropped by more than half within a decade of the PRC's foundation, a policy achievement produced to a large extent through the personal and family ties of the maternalist policy coalition that led the reform movement. However, these achievements were undermined or reversed in the complex policy struggles over the family during Mao's Great Leap Forward (1958–60).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFamiliesxPolitical aspectszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aInterpersonal relationsxPolitical aspectszChina. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzChina. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aWOMEN'S HISTORY. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh  aGreat Leap Forward, family ties in politics, gender and Maoist China, gender and state building, Chinese maternalism, May Fourth Movement, Chinese suffrage, All China Women’s Federation, Cai Chang.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150